data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work as expected:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[5];
```

On this 64-bit system, `nint.Size` is 8 bytes, so each element is pointer-sized. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types — they're valid in all contexts where other unmanaged value types work, including `stackalloc`.
